A regular hexagon can be divided into six equilateral triangles. Each triangle has a perimeter of 21 inches. 

First, we find the side length of each equilateral triangle:
\[
\text{Perimeter of one triangle} = 21 \text{ inches}
\]
\[
\text{Side length of each triangle} = \frac{21}{3} = 7 \text{ inches}
\]

Since each side of the equilateral triangle is equal to the side length of the hexagon, the side length of the hexagon is 7 inches.

Next, we calculate the perimeter of the regular hexagon. A regular hexagon has six sides:
\[
\text{Perimeter of the hexagon} = 6 \times \text{side length} = 6 \times 7 = 42 \text{ inches}
\]

Thus, the perimeter of the regular hexagon is \boxed{42} inches.
