To determine how many different battalions can be sent to fight at Thermopylae, we need to calculate the number of ways to choose 4 upper class soldiers out of 5 and 8 lower class soldiers out of 10. This is a combinatorics problem involving combinations.

First, we calculate the number of ways to choose 4 upper class soldiers from 5:

$$
C(5, 4) = \frac{5!}{4!(5 - 4)!} = \frac{5!}{4! \cdot 1!} = \frac{120}{24 \cdot 1} = 5
$$

Next, we calculate the number of ways to choose 8 lower class soldiers from 10. This is equivalent to choosing 2 lower class soldiers from 10:

$$
C(10, 8) = C(10, 2) = \frac{10!}{2!(10 - 2)!} = \frac{10 \times 9}{2 \times 1} = 45
$$

The total number of different battalions is the product of these two combinations:

$$
\text{Total battalions} = C(5, 4) \times C(10, 8) = 5 \times 45 = 225
$$

Thus, the number of different battalions that can be sent is \boxed{225}.
