Let me calculate that:

Perimeter of hexagon = number of sides × side length
Perimeter of hexagon = 6 × 16 cm

Hmm, 6 times 16. Let me compute that. 6 times 10 is 60, and 6 times 6 is 36, so 60 + 36 is 96. So, the perimeter of the hexagon is 96 cm.

Alright, so the octagon has the same perimeter, which is 96 cm. Now, since it's a regular octagon, all eight sides are equal. So, to find the length of each side, I can take the total perimeter and divide it by the number of sides.

Let me write that down:

Side length of octagon = Perimeter of octagon / number of sides
Side length of octagon = 96 cm / 8

Hmm, 96 divided by 8. Let me compute that. 8 goes into 96 twelve times because 8 times 12 is 96. So, each side of the octagon is 12 cm long.

Wait, let me double-check my calculations to make sure I didn't make a mistake. So, the hexagon has 6 sides, each 16 cm, so 6 times 16 is indeed 96 cm. Then, the octagon has 8 sides, so 96 divided by 8 is 12. Yep, that seems right.

I guess another way to think about it is that each side of the octagon is shorter than each side of the hexagon because the octagon has more sides. Since 8 is more than 6, each side must be shorter to keep the total perimeter the same. So, 16 cm sides become 12 cm sides. That makes sense.

Just to visualize, a hexagon has six sides, each 16 cm, so each side is quite long. An octagon has eight sides, so each side is a bit shorter to compensate and keep the same total perimeter. So, 12 cm per side for the octagon seems reasonable.

I don't think I made any mistakes here. The calculations are straightforward, and the logic follows. So, I think the side length of the octagon is 12 cm.

